<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike still wines, <strong>Prosecco's aging potential varies dramatically by quality level</strong>, with most styles designed for immediate enjoyment rather than long-term cellaring. Understanding these differences is crucial for maximizing your investment.</p>

<h3>Quality-Based Aging Potential</h3>

<p><strong>Prosecco DOC</strong> should be consumed within 1-2 years of purchase, as the fresh fruit character and vibrant acidity that define these wines quickly diminish. <strong>Prosecco DOCG Conegliano Valdobbiadene</strong> can develop beautifully for 3-5 years, gaining honeyed complexity while retaining its signature mineral backbone. Premium <strong>Cartizze</strong> represents the pinnacle, capable of aging gracefully for 8-10 years, developing notes of brioche, dried fruit, and enhanced textural richness.</p>

<h3>Evolution and Peak Windows</h3>

<p>Young Prosecco showcases bright citrus and green apple flavors with floral aromatics. As it ages, the wine develops <strong>secondary characteristics</strong>: the primary fruit evolves from fresh to dried, acidity softens slightly, and autolytic notes emerge—particularly in wines aged on lees. Vintage Prosecco from top producers like Bisol or Nino Franco hits its peak around year 4-6, when fruit intensity balances perfectly with developed complexity.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>

<p>Store Prosecco at <strong>50-55°F with 70% humidity</strong>, keeping bottles horizontal to maintain cork moisture. Unlike Champagne, Prosecco's Charmat method production makes it more sensitive to temperature fluctuations—even brief exposure to heat above 70°F can prematurely age the wine.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage</h3>

<p>Properly aged Prosecco develops golden hues and honeyed aromatics while maintaining bright acidity. <strong>Warning signs of spoilage</strong> include brown coloration, flat bubbles that dissipate immediately, and oxidized aromas reminiscent of sherry or bruised apples. When in doubt, younger is almost always better with Prosecco.</p>

