    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I keep an opened bottle of Prosecco fresh?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Unlike still wines, Prosecco loses its signature effervescence quickly once opened, staying fresh for only 1-3 days in the refrigerator with a proper sparkling wine stopper. Higher-quality DOCG Proseccos with finer bubbles may retain carbonation slightly longer than DOC versions. For best results, consume within 24 hours or use day-old Prosecco in cooking applications like risotto or poaching fruit.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good alternatives to Prosecco that offer similar value?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Franciacorta DOCG provides more complexity through traditional method production but costs 2-3 times more than premium Prosecco. For budget-conscious buyers, Spanish Cava offers traditional method quality at Prosecco DOC prices, while French Crémant provides regional diversity with similar pricing to mid-range Prosecco. However, none match Prosecco's unique combination of fresh fruit character, soft bubbles, and food-friendly acidity at its price point.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Prosecco style works best for beginners who find sparkling wine too acidic?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Extra Dry Prosecco offers the perfect entry point with 12-17g/L residual sugar that softens the wine's natural acidity while maintaining refreshing character. Look for producers from the warmer Treviso plains rather than steep Valdobbiadene hillsides, as these wines tend to be rounder and more approachable. Avoid Brut styles initially, and consider serving slightly warmer (45-48°F) to reduce perceived acidity.</p>
